# cursorProxy Core Context

- `cursorProxy` is an edge-compatible multi-provider AI proxy for DeepSeek, Kimi, MiniMax, Xiaomi MiMo, GLM / ZHIPU AI, Azure Foundry, and generic OpenAI/Anthropic-compatible endpoints.
- `api/proxy.js` is the main entrypoint and holds the provider orchestration (auth, model/alias resolution, body sanitization, header assembly, fetch + retries, non-streaming response mapping). Its extracted concerns live in `lib/`:
  - `lib/providers.js` — `PROVIDERS` registry, `buildUrl()` URL/path remapping, `upstreamApiKey`, upstream path safety.
  - `lib/responses-chain.js` — `previous_response_id` KV chaining (`prepareResponsesChain`) and the stateless retry (`retryPreviousResponseFailure`) for azureopenai + openaicompat Responses mode.
  - `lib/stream-pump.js` — the streaming SSE pump (`startStreamPump`): per-provider SSE transforms, reasoning/thinking accumulation + KV writes, stream timeout.
  - `lib/strict-tools.js` — strict-tool stats probe (`strictToolStats` is re-exported from `api/proxy.js` for tests).
  - `lib/cursor-tools.js` — Cursor Subagent/Task/Shell tool-arg sanitizers and Responses tool-arg remappers.
  - `lib/log-shapes.js` — log-formatting helpers (no logging side effects).
- `lib/models.js` handles model parsing, public/private model IDs, and provider routing.
- Azure adapters live in `lib/azure-openai.js` and `lib/azure-anthropic.js`.
- Kimi K2.x request sanitization lives in `lib/kimi.js` (`sanitizeKimiBody`); default Kimi model is `kimi-k2.7-code`.
- GLM request sanitization lives in `lib/glm.js` (`sanitizeGlmBody`); default GLM model is `glm-5.2`, default upstream is `https://open.bigmodel.cn/api/coding/paas/v4`, and global Z.AI uses `UPSTREAM_GLM=https://api.z.ai/api/coding/paas/v4`. GLM-5.2+ supports `reasoning_effort` (default `max`), overridable via the `GLM_REASONING_EFFORT` env var (precedence: env > client > default `max`); older GLM models have it stripped automatically.
- Reasoning and cache helpers live in `lib/reasoning.js`, `lib/cache.js`, and `lib/kv.js`.
- `api/proxy.js` and all `lib/*.js` files are shared edge-safe modules. Do not introduce `node:*` imports or `ioredis` there.
- `server.js` is the Docker-only wrapper around the shared proxy logic.
- `vercel.json` and `cloud-functions/` provide platform routing entrypoints.
- `cliProxy` at `/home/opc/cliProxy` is the sibling reference implementation for EdgeOne Pages deployment (see `.cursor/rules/edgeone-deployment.mdc`).
- Manual verification prompts live under `.cursor/test-cases/`.
- `wiki/` is a separate git clone for the GitHub wiki. Do not commit wiki changes in the main repo.
- Real Docker production logs are in Axiom dataset `cursorproxy`; use `.cursor/rules/axiom-prod-log-investigation.mdc` for post-release and troubleshooting log checks.
- The public wiki is for end users and operators: setup, deployment, configuration, provider behavior, troubleshooting, and operational trade-offs. Do not put developer-only implementation guidance, file ownership inventories, function-level checklists, internal cache-key design, log contracts, provider-addition workflows, commit hashes, helper/schema internals, or coding-agent lessons in the public wiki; put those in `.cursor/rules/` instead. When documenting cache modes such as `halo` and `passion8`, describe operator-visible behavior and selection criteria, not the commit history or internal schema/property names that led to the mode.
- For every new feature, provider, behavior change, env var, deployment change, or operator-facing fix, explicitly evaluate whether the GitHub wiki needs updating. If it does, update `wiki/` with user/operator-facing content in the same work so docs ship with the code change; if it is developer-only, update `.cursor/rules/` instead and be ready to state why the wiki did not change.
- Keep `README.md` minimal and quick-start focused. Put optional configuration, provider-specific details, troubleshooting, tuning knobs, and long user-facing explanations in the wiki, then link from the README instead of expanding it.
- **Release process — THREE STEPS, two review gates, never auto-advance past a pause**:

  - **Step 1 (default — do proactively): local edits + commit.** Make edits, write tests, update wiki and rules, then `git commit` to the local branch (main repo and `wiki/` as appropriate). Do NOT `git push`, do NOT tag, do NOT `gh release create`. **PAUSE here and wait.** A separate review tool runs against the local commit.

  - **Step 2 (only after review sign-off): push the branch.** On explicit confirmation that review passed (e.g. "push", "looks good", "go ahead", "GA", or review feedback that has been addressed with a new Step 1 commit), `git push origin <branch>` (main repo) and `git push origin master` inside `wiki/`. Branch pushes trigger Vercel/EdgeOne/Docker auto-redeploy. Do NOT tag, do NOT `gh release create`. **PAUSE here and wait** if not also proceeding to Step 3.

  - **Step 3 (on any explicit standalone "GA" mention): tag and release.** Treat a user message that includes `GA` as its own word (for example, "project can GA", "go GA now", or simply "GA") as Step 3 approval. Do not require `GA` to be the entire message, but do not match it inside another word. Review feedback, "go ahead", "push and release", "next step", "deploy", silence, and other messages that do not mention standalone `GA` remain Step 1 or Step 2 work — never Step 3. On a standalone `GA` mention, run the full sequence in one turn:
    1. Find the previous tag: `git tag --sort=-v:refname | head -5`.
    2. Determine the bump from `code-conventions.mdc` (patch = fixes/docs; minor = new provider or operator-facing feature; major = breaking).
    3. Confirm the target commit is already pushed (Step 2 handles this; if not, push now).
    4. Create the annotated tag with NO description body, using the commit's date as tagger date so tags sort chronologically on GitHub:
       `GIT_COMMITTER_DATE="<commit-date>" git tag -a vX.Y.Z <commit> -m "vX.Y.Z"`.
    5. Push the tag: `git push origin vX.Y.Z`.
    6. Create the GitHub release with full changelog comparing against the previous tag:
       `gh release create vX.Y.Z --notes "..."` (notes via heredoc).

  Tags must never carry descriptions; descriptions belong only on GitHub Releases. Never assume advancement from silence or from any phrase that isn't the explicit trigger for the next step.

- **Provider implementation checklist — lessons from Fireworks integration** (these apply to every new provider):

  - **0 — Read upstream docs before writing any code.** See the global rule in `/home/opc/AGENTS.md` ("Verify Before You Implement"). For every new provider, fetch the official API reference, model catalog, and any reasoning/streaming/auth docs *before* touching `api/proxy.js` or `lib/models.js`. Do not assume endpoint URLs, model ID formats, or parameter semantics from "it's OpenAI-compatible."

  - **Do not use localhost server runs as cursorProxy validation.** For this project, the local environment is not sufficient to prove runtime behavior because deployment routing, KV availability, platform headers, and real operator env vars differ from production. Do not bring up `server.js` on `localhost` to validate provider behavior or cache behavior unless the user explicitly asks for a local smoke test. Use focused automated tests for code-level verification, then use deployed/provided runtime logs or user-triggered real traffic for cursorProxy behavior.

  - **Keep provider probing separate from cursorProxy parameter design.** The `.cursor/skills/cursorproxy-provider-probe` skill is only for detecting remote provider cache-hit combinations and API behavior across Responses and Chat modes. Do not merge cursorProxy-specific env-mode design into that skill, and do not treat probe output as proof that a local cursorProxy server is correctly configured. Probe first to identify the upstream combination; implement/verify cursorProxy separately.

  - **Model ID routing: map ALL ID variants.** When a provider uses non-standard model IDs (e.g. `accounts/<account>/models/<id>`), update `providerFromModel()` in `lib/models.js` to recognize: (a) the proxy's own prefix for disambiguation, (b) the provider's native fully-qualified format, (c) bare model names sent via the provider's route path. All three must route to the provider.

  - **Test fixture IDs must match the upstream catalog.** The proxy does not translate model names — it prefixes them. If tests and docs use made-up model IDs, they pass locally but produce nonexistent upstream IDs. Always validate test fixture model names against the provider's published model catalog before finalizing tests.

  - **Reasoning injection gates: always provide an explicit bypass.** Model-name heuristics (family regexes, `-no-thinking` suffixes) will miss edge cases. Always allow the client to override via `reasoning_history` (`"preserved"`, `"interleaved"`, `"disabled"`) and `thinking.keep` / `thinking.type`. When the client sets these explicitly, honor them regardless of what the model-name regex says.

  - **New providers that host heterogeneous models should default to hit-only reasoning restoration.** Never fabricate `"(prior reasoning unavailable)"` placeholders for providers where some hosted models lack reasoning support. The hit-only path (restore cached reasoning, skip on miss) is always safe; placeholders are only safe when every model the provider hosts unconditionally requires the reasoning field.

  - **Reasoning scope isolation: include the upstream model name.** When reasoning caches are shared across models (e.g. a provider hosting 200+ models), scope KV keys by `provider:upstreamModelName:user` rather than just `provider:user`. A reasoning trace from one model family injected into another family's request will be silently wrong.

  - **Interleaved reasoning has three distinct paths, not one:**
    1. `reasoning_history: "disabled"` → skip injection entirely.
    2. `reasoning_history` explicitly `"interleaved"` or model-default interleaved + user-ending → skip injection (upstream discards reasoning before the last user message).
    3. `reasoning_history: "interleaved"` + tool-ending → inject, but only for assistant turns after the last user message (older turns are stripped by upstream anyway).

  - **Model-default behavior detection must handle canonical name variants.** Providers may use dotted (`kimi-k2.6`) or `p`-separated (`kimi-k2p6`) canonical form depending on context. Default-behavior detection regexes must match both. Use `== null` (not `=== undefined`) to catch both `undefined` and `null` for optional fields. Include all model families that share the default, not just the first one found.

  - **Response model aliasing: always force for providers with internal ID mapping.** If the proxy rewrites `parsedBody.model` to a different upstream ID, call `withPublicResponseModel(json, responseModelName, forceAlias=true)` so the response `model` field reflects the client-requested ID. The upstream's `model` field in the response will NOT match what the client sent.

  - **OpenAI-compatible cache tuning is probe-first and mode-selective.** For generic `openaicompat` providers, use `.cursor/skills/cursorproxy-provider-probe` to test direct upstream `/v1/responses`, Chat-boundary Responses mode, and Chat Completions mode separately, then choose the single best runtime mode for that provider deployment. Do not adapt both Chat and Responses modes just because one provider needs special handling. If a provider's dashboard confirms Chat cache hits via `prompt_cache_key + Session_id` but HTTP `previous_response_id` is unsupported, tune `OPENAICOMPAT_WIRE_API=chat` + `OPENAICOMPAT_CHAT_CACHE_MODE=remote` and leave Responses mode unchanged for providers that already work. Only change Responses-mode behavior when the probe and provider logs show the target provider's best strategy actually depends on Responses mode.

  - **When an OpenAI-compatible provider does not work well, use real upstream credentials and probe before adding knobs.** Ask the operator to put the provider API key/base URL in env (or provide a safe probe environment), run `.cursor/skills/cursorproxy-provider-probe`, and compare the provider's confirmed behavior against the current mode matrix: Chat mode (`OPENAICOMPAT_CHAT_CACHE_MODE=passthrough|facade|remote`) versus Responses mode (`OPENAICOMPAT_CACHE_HIT_MODE=default|sub2api|halo|passion8`). `halo` and `passion8` share Halo prompt/session handling, diagnostics, the `"halo"` `oairesp:` scope, stateless-first tool output, `GetMcpTools` cleanup, and ordinary done-argument repair; only `halo` widens `CallMcpTool.parameters.properties.arguments`. Use `passion8` to preserve pre-`2111555` Halo behavior for a vendor that already works without that nested schema repair, and use `halo` only when provider evidence proves the repair is needed. Add a new env option only when the probe plus deployed logs show a distinct, repeatable upstream contract that cannot be represented by the existing values; do not overload an existing value with provider-specific behavior.
